{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501256"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.24,0.2,0.01,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94520"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"725"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94520"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with right upper quadrant discomfort for three days. She is concerned about her kidneys as her sister recently started peritoneal dialysis for an unknown kidney condition. She has no urinary symptoms, fever, or haematuria. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild right upper quadrant tenderness without guarding or rebound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ultrasound shows a hypoechoic renal lesion and no other abnormalities. The patient\u0027s discomfort settles. A subsequent CT scan demonstrates a single simple cyst in the lower pole of the right kidney measuring 3 cm in diameter with thin walls, no septations, and homogeneous fluid density (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Genetic testing for PKD1","Percutaneous needle biopsy","Ureteral stenting","Repeat ultrasound in three months"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidentally discovered simple renal cyst on imaging. Simple renal cysts are the most common kidney masses, accounting for 65-70% of cases. They are more prevalent in people over 50 years of age and in men. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as simple renal cysts are benign and typically require no treatment or follow-up. Despite the family history of kidney disease, a single simple cyst with classic imaging features does not warrant further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing for PKD1\u003C/strong\u003E, a gene associated with polycystic kidney disease, would be inappropriate as this patient has a single simple cyst. Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease typically presents with multiple bilateral cysts and enlarged kidneys. The presence of a single cyst in a 52-year-old is more likely to be age-related than hereditary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for indeterminate renal masses where imaging is inconclusive. In this case, imaging clearly shows a simple cyst with classic features (thin wall, no septations, homogeneous fluid density). Additionally, biopsy of complex cysts is generally avoided due to the risk of seeding if malignant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteral stenting\u003C/strong\u003E is used to relieve urinary obstruction, typically from stones or external compression. There is no evidence of obstruction in this case, and simple renal cysts rarely cause obstruction unless very large.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in three months\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for a simple renal cyst. While some complex cysts (Bosniak IIF or higher) require surveillance, simple cysts do not need routine follow-up unless symptomatic. The classic imaging features on CT are sufficient to confirm benignity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising typical features of simple renal cysts on imaging (round, smooth-walled, fluid-filled) and distinguishing them from complex cysts or other renal masses that might require further investigation or follow-up. The patient can be reassured that her right upper quadrant pain is unlikely to be related to this incidental finding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Simple renal cysts are common incidental findings, accounting for 65-70% of kidney masses on imaging","Simple renal cysts require no treatment or follow-up if asymptomatic and clearly benign on imaging","Complex renal cysts may require follow-up based on Bosniak classification","Family history of kidney disease alone does not warrant investigation of incidental simple renal cysts"],"references":["Kruskal JB, Jerome, PR Jerome. Simple and complex kidney cysts in adults. In: Uptodate [online]. 2021 [cited 2021 Aug 9]. Available at: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/simple-and-complex-kidney-cysts-in-adults\u003E","Khan MQ, Ponor IL, Ross AE, Khaliq W. Management of a simple renal cyst in a complex patient. BMJ Case Rep. 2013 Jun 5;2013:bcr2013009270.Available at: https://casereports.bmj.com/content/2013/bcr-2013-009270","Bosniak M A. The Bosniak Renal Cyst Classification: 25 Years Later. Radiology 2011; 262:781\u201385. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22357882/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77560"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14634"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14634"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ec632349-b557-46af-a55b-c4ca5679aba4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ec632349-b557-46af-a55b-c4ca5679aba4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":457,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77560"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T12:19:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T12:20:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94520"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","